Linear Model

How does assuming linearity help? Which of the following functions is easier to estimate?

\[Y = f(X_1, X_2, X_3) + \epsilon\]

or

\[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 + \beta_3 X_3 + \epsilon\]

In a linear model \(\textit{parameters enter linearly}!\) Which one of the following is a linear model or can be written as a linear model?

  1. \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 logX2 + \beta_3 X_1 X_2 + \epsilon\)
  2. \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1^{\beta_2} + \epsilon\)
  3. \(Y = \beta_0 X_1^{\beta_1}\epsilon\)

Estimating \(\beta\)

Geometric Interpretation

Geometric interpretation of least squares.

\[Data = \text{Systematic Structure} + \text{Random Variation}\] \[\text{n dimentions} = \text{p dimentions} + \text{(n-p) dimentions}\]

Goodness of Fit

\(R^2\), coefficient of determination or percentage of variance explained, may be used as a measure of goodness of fit.

\[R^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum (\hat{y_i} - y_i)^2}{\sum (y_i - \bar{y})^2} = 1 - \frac{RSS}{TSS}\]

Variation in y conditioned on knowing X vs not knowing X

Transformations

Transformations of the response and predictors can improve the fit and correct violations of the model assumptions e.g. nonconstant error variance. We also can add function of multiple predictors. Can you think of some common ones?

Read in savings dataset:

savings <- read.table("savings.csv", header = TRUE,
                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE, sep = ",")

Transforming the Predictors

  1. Box-Cox for each predictor.
  2. \(x \rightarrow f(x)\) and look at the partial residual plots which provides more flexibility.

Broken Stick Regression

Sometimes we believe that different linear regression models apply in different regions of the data. Let’s examine the savings dataset:

Now go ahead and read in this dataset. For this exercise we will only focus on the relationship between sr and pop15.

  1. Fit a regression line to a subset of the data with \(pop15 < 35\) and \(pop15 > 35\) separately.
  2. Make a scatter plot of the data and plot the fitted lines using segments()
g1 <- lm(sr ~ pop15, savings, subset = (pop15 < 35))
g2 <- lm(sr ~ pop15, savings, subset = (pop15 > 35))
plot(sr ~ pop15, savings, xlab = "Population under 15", ylab = "Savings Rate")
abline(v = 35, lty = 5)
segments(20, g1$coeff[1] + g1$coeff[2]*20, 35, g1$coeff[1] + g1$coeff[2]*35)
segments(35, g2$coeff[1] + g2$coeff[2]*35, 48, g2$coeff[1] + g2$coeff[2]*48)

One might have a reason to look for a continuous fit. One can enforce this continuity by introducing new variables:

\[ B_l(x) = \begin{cases} c - x & x < c \\ 0 & otherwise \end{cases} \]

\[ B_r(x) = \begin{cases} x - c & x > c \\ 0 & otherwise \end{cases} \]

Where \(c\) is the division between the two groups. Now we can fit the following model:

\[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1B_l(x) + \beta_2B_r(x) + \epsilon \]

As an exercise transform the pop15 variable and fit a linear model to it. Then plot the result.

lhs <- function(x) ifelse(x < 35 , 35 - x, 0)
rhs <- function(x) ifelse(x < 35 , 0, x - 35)
gb <- lm(sr ~ lhs(pop15) + rhs(pop15), savings)
x <- seq(20,48,by = 1)
py <- gb$coeff[1] + gb$coeff[2]*lhs(x) + gb$coeff[3]*rhs(x)

plot(sr ~ pop15, savings, xlab = "Population under 15", ylab = "Savings Rate")
abline(v = 35, lty = 5)
segments(20, g1$coeff[1] + g1$coeff[2]*20, 35, g1$coeff[1] + g1$coeff[2]*35)
segments(35, g2$coeff[1] + g2$coeff[2]*35, 48, g2$coeff[1] + g2$coeff[2]*48)

lines(x,py, lty = 2)
